A high level of lexical similarity exists between German language|German and Dutch language|Dutch,<ref>Cite news |url=http://languagetsar.com/how-similar-or-different-are-german-and-dutch/ |title=German and Dutch: similar or different? |last= |first= |date=2016-11-17 |work=Language Tsar |access-date=2018-02-15 |archive-url= |archive-date= |dead-url= |language=en-US</ref> but shifts in meaning of words with a shared etymology have in some instances resulted in 'bi-directional false friends':<ref>Cite web |url=http://www.uitmuntend.de/extras/valse_vrienden.html |title=''valse vrienden – Falsche Freunde'' |last= |first= |date= |website=uitmuntend.de |language=nl,de |access-date=2018-02-15</ref><ref>Cite web |url=https://www.nubeterduits.nl/website/index.php?pag=132 |title=''dürfen / müssen / sollen / mögen'' |last= |first= |date= |website=nubeterduits.nl |language=nl |access-date=2018-02-15</ref>
